
# ServiceNow Capstone Project Learning Notes

---

# Task 1 Learning

## Custom Fields

A custom field stores additional business information not available in the default table structure.

Example:

sFone Model

Added to Incident table to store device model information.

---

## Dictionary Entry

A Dictionary Entry defines:

- Field Type
- Field Length
- Label
- Attributes

Every field created in ServiceNow automatically creates a Dictionary Entry.

---

## Choice Lists

Choice Lists provide predefined values to users.

Benefits:

- Data consistency
- Reduced input errors
- Standardization

Example:

Category = sFone

---

## Form Layout

Form Layout controls:

- Field visibility
- Field placement
- User experience

---

# Task 2 Learning

## User Administration

User Administration manages:

- Users
- Groups
- Roles

within ServiceNow.

---

## Users

Users represent individual people who access the platform.

Example:

- Fred Luddy
- Bud Richman
- David Loo

---

## Groups

Groups collect users together for:

- Assignment
- Collaboration
- Work Distribution

Example:

Strawberry Support Group

---

## Roles

Roles define permissions.

Example:

itil

allows access to ITSM operations.

---

## RBAC

Role-Based Access Control controls access using roles.

Instead of assigning permissions directly to users:

User → Group → Role → Access

Benefits:

- Security
- Scalability
- Easier Administration

Example:

Strawberry Support Group received itil role.

All group members inherit required permissions.

---

## Manager Relationships

Managers help support:

- Approvals
- Escalations
- Reporting

Example:

Kara Prince → Manager = Fred Luddy

---

# Task 3 Learning

## Service Catalog

Service Catalog provides a self-service portal for requesting:

- Hardware
- Software
- Services
- Mobile Devices

Benefits:

- Standardized Requests
- Faster Fulfillment
- Better Tracking

---

## Catalog Item

A Catalog Item represents a product or service users can request.

Example:

Strawberry sFone

---

## Request Lifecycle

User Request

↓

REQ (Request)

↓

RITM (Requested Item)

↓

SCTASK (Catalog Tasks)

↓

Fulfillment

↓

Completion

---

## Request (REQ)

REQ represents the overall request.

Example:

REQ0010001

Acts like a shopping cart.

---

## Requested Item (RITM)

RITM represents an individual requested item.

Example:

Strawberry sFone

One REQ may contain multiple RITMs.

---

## Catalog Tasks (SCTASK)

Catalog Tasks break fulfillment into manageable activities.

Examples:

- Order Device
- Configure Device
- Deliver Device

---

## Flow Designer

Flow Designer automates business processes without coding.

Capabilities:

- Triggers
- Actions
- Approvals
- Conditions
- Notifications

---

## Approval Workflow

Manager approval ensures:

- Governance
- Budget Control
- Authorization

Before fulfillment begins.

---

## Workflow Automation

Automation reduces:

- Manual work
- Errors
- Delays

while improving consistency.

---

## Flow Logic Used

Trigger:
Catalog Item Requested

↓

Ask For Approval

↓

If Approved

↓

Create Task 1

↓

Create Task 2

↓

Create Task 3

↓

Close Requested Item

Else

↓

Send Rejection Email

↓

End Flow

